  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The symptom of blue smoke on startup that clears after a minute is a classic indicator of oil burning, specifically oil seeping past the valve stem seals or worn valve guides into the combustion chambers while the engine is off. Once the engine starts, this accumulated oil burns off. The FSM lists 'Worn valve guides' as a potential engine fault (Source 34, 60). To assess the overall mechanical condition of the engine and differentiate between valve train wear and piston ring issues, a compression test and a manifold vacuum test are the appropriate next steps, as the FSM directs to 'Perform a manifold vacuum or engine compression test to determine which mechanical component of the engine is at fault' (Source 34, 60). A malfunctioning Positive Crankcase Ventilation (PCV) system can also contribute to oil consumption by allowing excessive crankcase pressure to force oil past seals (Source 34, 60).",
  "mechanic_instructions": "That blue puff on startup, clearing after a minute, is oil burning. It's a classic sign of oil seeping past worn valve stem seals or valve guides into the combustion chambers while the engine sits. When you fire it up, that accumulated oil burns off. To get a clear picture of the engine's internal health and confirm this, you need to perform a compression test on all cylinders and a manifold vacuum test. This will tell us if we're looking at valve train issues, or if there's a deeper problem with the piston rings. Also, check the PCV system for clogs or restrictions.",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "All cylinders show good, consistent compression, and the manifold vacuum gauge reads steady within the normal operating range.",
    "One or more cylinders show significantly lower compression, or there's a wide variation between cylinders. The manifold vacuum gauge is low or fluctuates erratically.",
    "I found the PCV valve clogged or the hoses restricted."
  ],
  "requires_input": true
}

