  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The loud ticking or hissing sound, especially when cold and quieting when warm, points to either a noisy hydraulic valve lifter or a vacuum/exhaust leak. A noisy hydraulic valve lifter is a common cause of a ticking sound that is more pronounced with cold, thicker oil and can quiet as the engine warms and oil thins, as described in the FSM (Source 14, page 20). A hissing sound, particularly one that changes with temperature, is characteristic of a vacuum leak (e.g., intake manifold or carburetor gasket) or an exhaust leak. As the engine warms, metal expansion can temporarily seal these leaks. The FSM lists 'Leakage intake manifold or carburetor gaskets' as a potential issue (Source 18, page 47). Pinpointing the exact nature and location of the sound is critical for the next diagnostic step.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "Listen closely to the engine to determine if the sound is primarily a metallic 'ticking' or an air 'hissing.' Also, try to localize the sound to a specific area of the engine. This will help differentiate between a valve train issue and a leak.",
