  "diagnostic_reasoning": "A steady oil drip under the back of the engine near the transmission can originate from several sources. My primary hypothesis is a rear main crankshaft seal leak, as this is a common failure point in this area. However, the FSM (Source 1, page 11) explicitly states that engine oil leaks are often misdiagnosed as front pump seal leaks and lists other potential sources, including rocker arm cover leaks, oil gallery plug leaks, and even converter drain plug leaks (Source 28, page 11). The FSM also mentions the oil pan rear seal (Source 40, page 12). To accurately diagnose, the first step is to determine if the fluid is engine oil or transmission fluid. Original factory transmission fluid is dyed red (Source 1, page 11), which will help differentiate. This initial observation will funnel the diagnosis towards either the engine or the transmission.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "A steady drip at the engine-to-transmission junction requires careful identification of the fluid. Engine oil leaks are often mistaken for transmission front pump seal leaks. Before we proceed, remove the transmission dipstick and note the color of the fluid. Original factory-fill automatic transmission fluid is dyed red. This will help us determine if the leak is engine oil or transmission fluid.",
