  "diagnostic_reasoning": "An oil leak from the front of the engine, behind the pulley, most commonly indicates a failure of the crankshaft front oil seal or the cylinder front cover gasket. The FSM mentions oil slingers preventing leakage from the crankshaft front oil seal (Source 35, page 41) and procedures for replacing the front oil seal (Source 47, page 47; Source 51, page 48). The cylinder front cover gasket is also a potential source (Source 57, page 49). Additionally, the fuel pump, located at the front of the engine, can leak engine oil if its diaphragm is defective or the pull rod oil seal is ruptured (Source 6, page 46; Source 7, page 7). The oil pan front seal is another possibility (Source 52, page 36). To accurately diagnose, the area must be cleaned and observed as the leak develops, similar to the general leak detection procedure outlined for the converter area (Source 1, page 11; Source 29, page 12).",
  "mechanic_instructions": "An oil leak from the very front of the engine, behind the pulley area, points to a few critical components. The most common culprits are the crankshaft front oil seal, the cylinder front cover gasket, or the fuel pump. To accurately pinpoint the source, you need to perform a thorough visual inspection after cleaning. First, clean the entire front of the engine, specifically around the crankshaft pulley, the cylinder front cover, and the fuel pump mounting area, using a suitable non-flammable solvent. Blow the area dry with compressed air. Then, start the engine and let it run at idle. Observe the cleaned area closely for the first signs of oil leakage.",
