  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The reported symptoms—engine overheating, milky-brown sludge under the oil cap, and small bubbles in the radiator—are classic indicators of internal engine leakage. The bubbles in the radiator confirm combustion gases are entering the cooling system, as stated in the FSM: 'Internal leakage can be detected by operating the engine at fast idle and looking for the formation of bubbles in the radiator.' (Source 11). The milky-brown sludge under the oil cap indicates coolant mixing with engine oil, which the FSM notes as 'Water formation on the oil level dipstick engine could also be an indication of internal leakage.' (Source 11). Overheating is a direct consequence of such internal leaks compromising cooling system efficiency. The most common component-level failure causing all three symptoms is a defective cylinder head gasket, or a crack in the cylinder head or engine block. The FSM lists 'Cylinder head gasket defective. Cracked cylinder head or block, or warped cylinder head Or block gasket surface.' as causes for 'ENGINE OVERHEATS' and 'LOSS OF COOLANT' (Source 15).",
  "mechanic_instructions": "The bubbles in the radiator confirm combustion gases are entering the cooling system, and the milky sludge indicates coolant in the oil. This points to a breach between the combustion chambers, cooling system, and lubrication system, most commonly a defective cylinder head gasket, or a cracked head or block.\n\nFirst, pull the engine oil dipstick and examine the oil for water formation or a milky appearance. This will confirm the extent of coolant contamination in the oil.\n\nSecond, remove all spark plugs. Inspect the electrodes and insulator noses for any signs of fouling, specifically white, burned, or blistered deposits, or unusually clean plugs, which can indicate coolant burning in a cylinder (Source 4).",
