  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The combination of rough idle, lost power, and hard starting points to a fuel mixture issue, specifically a rich condition. A common cause for this in the Autolite 2100 carburetor is a leaking power valve. The FSM states that 'Power valve leakage that causes an unadjustable rough engine idle condition can be diagnosed... by the fact that the idle mixture needle(s) must be nearly, or completely seated in order to obtain a relatively smooth engine idle condition.' (Source 2). A leaking power valve also contributes to poor acceleration and general rough running (Source 13, 24, 51). Other possibilities include incorrect idle adjustments, choke issues, or fuel pump problems, but the power valve is a strong candidate given the symptoms.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "The engine's rough idle, lost power, and hard starting suggest an overly rich fuel condition, potentially caused by a leaking power valve in the carburetor. A leaking power valve will allow too much fuel into the engine at idle and light throttle, making it run rough and lose power. To confirm this, check the current adjustment of the idle mixture screws. If the power valve is leaking, you will likely find the idle mixture screws turned in much further than their normal setting (typically 1-1.5 turns out from lightly seated) in an attempt to lean out the excessively rich mixture.",
